,"meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Alker</i>, <i>Auker</i>. This is derived either from Old English <i>Ealhhere</i> (composed of elements meaning ‘altar’ + ‘army’), or from Old French <i>Alcher</i>, <i>Aucher</i>, <i>Auqu(i)er</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Alchari</i>).","Americanized form of Dutch or German   Acker  . Compare   Aucker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Acker","meanings":["Dutch and German: topographic name from Middle High German and Middle Dutch <i>acker</i> ‘(cultivated) field’ (a cognate of the English word <i>acre</i>), hence a byname for a peasant (see   Ackerman  ). Compare   Achor  ,   Acre  ,   Acree  , and   Auker  .","English: habitational name from Castle Acre, South Acre, or West Acre in Norfolk; or a topographic name for someone living by a piece of cultivated land, from Middle English <i>aker</i>, <i>acre</i> ‘acre, field’ (Old English <i>æcer</i>). Compare   Akers  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Acker</i> ‘field’ (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Pet form of   Katherine  , derived from the pet form   Kit   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-y</i>. It is also used as an independent given name."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the na